Dump takes a vector of names of R objects and produces text representations of the objects on a file or connection,a dump file can usually be sourced into another R session. Save writes an external representation of R objects to the specified file,the objects can be read back from the file at a later date by using the function load or attach . so they are similar in both are present for R objects, the difference between them is that dump could be a source but save is doing rade back. after dump and save , if we remove the object we can get them back by source and load and it is same as the objects we created.

## question 3 
z =numeric()
x = runif(1000000) 
y = runif(1000000)
plot(x,y)
lines(seq(0,1,by=0.000001),sqrt((1/2)^2-(seq(0,1,by=0.000001)-(1/2))^2),col=2)

z=((x-(1/2))^2+(y-(1/2))^2<(1/2)^2)*4
pi.estimate=mean(z)
print("the pi estimate is")
## [1] "the pi estimate is"
pi.estimate
## [1] 3.141336
print("the varience is")
## [1] "the varience is"
var(z)
## [1] 2.697355
print("the confidence interval is")
## [1] "the confidence interval is"
confidenceinterval=c(pi.estimate+1.96*sqrt(var(z))/sqrt(1000000),pi.estimate-1.96*sqrt(var(z))/sqrt(1000000))
confidenceinterval
## [1] 3.144555 3.138117
